properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected midday today into Sunday. Total snowfall expected: 15 to 25 cm. Locations: Burin Peninsula, Avalon Peninsula, Clarenville and vicinity, Terra Nova, and Bonavista Peninsula. Time span: near noon today, until Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Snow will develop over the southern Avalon and Burin Peninsulas near midday today and spread across the east coast of Newfoundland later this afternoon. The snow will become heavy at times tonight. The snowfall rates will ease by Sunday morning and will end from the south to the north throughout the day. Occasional blowing snow will also develop tonight with strengthening northeasterly wind gusts. Blowing snow conditions will ease throughout Sunday as the snow ends and the winds gradually shift to northwesterly and begin to weaken. ### Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard developing today and ending late Sunday. A low pressure system crossing Hudson Bay continues to bring bitterly cold air over Kivalliq. Northwesterly winds of 50 gusting 70 km/h will develop at Naujaat and Coral Harbour today or tonight bringing blowing snow and blizzard conditions to those communities. The strong winds and blizzard conditions will continue tonight and into Sunday before diminishing late in the day. In addition, extreme wind chill values in the -55 to -60 range are already occurring and are expected to continue into Sunday as well before moderating. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential blizzard at Iqaluit Sunday. A low pressure system in Hudson Bay is crossing southern Baffin Island this weekend. As the system approaches the area today, light snow and southeasterly winds of 40 to 50 km/h will bring reduced visibilities in blowing snow for the day. However, much stronger winds are anticipated on Sunday once the system passes northeast of Iqaluit. There is potential for northwesterly winds of 60 gusting 80 km/h or more developing midday Sunday which will likely reduce visibilities to blizzard conditions. The strong winds are expected to continue into the evening before gradually diminishing on Monday morning. The current forecast track of the system passes very close to Iqaluit, and as such the strength and exact timing of the strongest winds may change as the low approaches the area. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills continues. Extreme cold wind chill values of -45 to -50 continue as bitterly cold arctic air settles over northern Manitoba in the wake of a departing low pressure system. While winds will diminish today and temperatures moderate this afternoon, the extreme cold is likely to return briefly tonight into Sunday morning as the cold airmass remains in place for another day. ### Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Sant at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. A Pacific weather system is spreading snow into central Saskatchewan today. This slowly moving low will track across southern Saskatchewan throughout the day and into Manitoba on Sunday. Most areas can expect 10 to 20 cm of snow by the time the system departs late Sunday, with the largest totals likely from the Lloydminster area east to the Manitoba border. Additionally, moderate northeasterly winds will accompany the snow today, causing visibilities to be reduced in blowing snow at times. Late this morning, radar indicates that the heaviest snow will fall to the north of Saskatoon and Kindersley. Saskatoon will likely end up with totals of 4 to 8 cm as they will be situated along the southern edge of the storm. The accompanying cold front will move through southern portions of the province tonight bringing flurries with a risk of freezing rain. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of very cold wind chills is expected. Extreme cold today with near-blizzard conditions. Extreme cold tonight and Sunday morning. Bitterly cold air with near-blizzard conditions remains in place over Kivalliq as a low pressure system crosses Hudson Bay and a ridge of high pressure builds to the west. With strong northwesterly winds up to 50 km/h continuing today, extreme cold wind chills of -55 to -60 will continue for most of the day and persist tonight. In addition, near-blizzard conditions can be expected for most of the day before improving late this afternoon or tonight. Winds will gradually begin to diminish over the area tonight and temperatures will moderate on Sunday. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Reduced visibilities due to snow and blowing snow today. Total snowfall: 5 cm, possibly reaching 10 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 90 km/h. Locations: Atlantic coastal regions of Nova Scotia. Time span: today and this evening. Remarks: At this time, the heaviest snow is expected to remain offshore of Nova Scotia. Although snowfall amounts are not expected to exceed 10 cm, visibilities will likely be low in blowing snow at times due the strong winds. The highest snowfall totals appears to be for Guysborough County, and eastern Cape Breton based on radar returns. Wind warnings are currently in effect for portions of the Atlantic coast of Nova Scotia and Cape Breton. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
